t 1168":"about 1168","Abt 1167":"about 1167","1113":"1113","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1175":"about 1175","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Windsor, Berkshire, England":"Windsor, Berkshire, England","Windsor,South Wales,Ireland":"Windsor, County Antrim, Ireland","Burnham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Burnham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Windsor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Windsor (Berkshire), Windsor in Stratford upon Avon (Warwickshire), Winsor in Copythorne (Hampshire), Winsor in Yealmpton (Devon), or Broadwindsor and Little Windsor (Dorset). All these places have the same linguistic origin, whose meaning is controversial, but seems to be ‘windlass bank’ (Old English <i>windels</i> + <i>ōra</i>).","in Yorkshire perhaps a habitational name from Winds Over in Middleton (near Ilkley, Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>wind</i> ‘wind’ (genitive <i>windes</i>) + <i>ofer</i> ‘slope, hill, ridge’."],"variants":[{"name":"Winzer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Ilse, Ingo, Wilhelm.","German: occupational name for a vine-grower or vintner, Middle High German <i>winzer</i>.","German: habitational name from any of various places so named in Bavaria."]},{"name":"Winsor","meanings":["English: variant of   Windsor  . This is the spelling used for places so named in Devon and Hampshire.","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Winzer  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Windsor was born in 1142, in Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Windsor I, was 43 and his mother, Gwaladus Verch Rhiwallon, was 30. He married Guinda Windsor about 1167, in Windsor, County Antrim, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"1142–":"1142–Surnud","1132–1176":"1132–1176","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1145–1205":"1145–1205","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1175–1203":"1175–1203","1100–1173":"1100–1173","1113–1142":"1113–1142","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1142":"1142","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","1205":"1205","1203":"1203","Abt 1168":"umbes 1168","Abt 1167":"umbes 1167","1113":"1113","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Windsor, Berkshire, England":"Windsor, Berkshire, England","Windsor,South Wales,Ireland":"Windsor, County Antrim, Iirimaa","Burnham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Burnham, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1142–":"1142–Kuo